In order for a signal installation to be recommended at a NMDOT intersection, a signal warrant study has
to be conducted. At least one of the following traffic signal warrants has to be met in order for the
intersection to be eligible for consideration for the placement of a traffic signal. The satisfaction of a
traffic signal warrant or warrants shall not in itself require the installation of a traffic control signal.
A traffic control signal will not be installed unless the engineering study indicates that installing a traffic
control signal will improve the overall safety and/or operation of the intersection.
In accordance with the Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices (MUTCD), this study may consider
the effects of the right-turn vehicles from the minor-street approaches. Engineering judgment should be
used to determine what, if any, portion of the right-turn traffic is subtracted from the minor-street traffic
count when evaluating the count against the above signal warrants.
The purpose of the traffic signal warrant study is to determine if the intersection of NM 564 and Boyd
Avenue meets the necessary warrants to be considered, by the NMDOT, for placement of a traffic signal.
The NMDOT has received a request from the City of Gallup (New Mexico) for the intersection to be
The intersection of NM 564 (Boardman Drive) and Boyd Avenue is located within the boundaries of
McKinley County, New Mexico. NM 564 is a state highway that runs east-west from NM 602 on the
south side of Gallup and then turns north-south along the east side of Gallup until it intersects NM 118
just south of I-40. NM 564 is classified as a minor arterial and provides access around the south and east
sides of Gallup, New Mexico. In the project area, NM 564 carries approximately 7,300 vehicles daily.
The roadway typical section on NM 564 consists of four 12-foot driving lanes, two in each direction
(northbound and southbound at the study intersection), and sidewalk on both sides. The posted speed
limit on NM 564 in the vicinity of the Boyd Avenue intersection is 45 miles per hour (mph).
Boyd Avenue is a 2-lane urban collector that proceeds east from NM 564. Boyd Avenue carries
approximately 900 vehicles per day. Boyd Avenue provides access to John Hopkins University, the First
Financial Credit Union, and the Gallup Municipal Court Building.
East of the NM 564 intersection, Boyd Avenue has two 12-foot driving lanes, one in each direction
(eastbound and westbound), and sidewalk on both sides. The posted speed limit is 25 miles per hour.
No west approach to the NM 564/Boyd Avenue intersection exists at the time of this study.

A signal warrant analysis was performed for the intersection of US 564 and Boyd Avenue. Traffic data
for both US 564 and Boyd Avenue were collected by Mike Henderson Consulting.
The following are the findings of the signal warrant analysis:

It is intended that Warrant 1 be treated as a single warrant. If Condition A is satisfied, then the
criteria for Warrant 1 is satisfied and Condition B and the combination of Conditions A and B are
not needed. Similarly, if Condition B is satisfied, then the criteria for Warrant 1 is satisfied and
the combination of Conditions A and B is not needed.

In applying each condition the major-street and minor-street volumes shall be for the same 8

The need for a traffic control signal shall be considered if an engineering study finds that both of

A. The vehicles per hour given in both of the 80 percent columns of Condition A in Table

page.text: For Condition A, with a 70% reduction factor applied since the speed limit on NM 564 exceeds
40 MPH, the warrant for a two-lane approach on the major street (NM 564) is 420 vehicles, and
that target was met 12 hours out of the 12 total hours that were counted.
The minor street (Boyd Avenue) warrant for a one-lane approach, which is 105 vehicles, was met
11 hours out of the 12 total hours that were counted.
The minor street warrant was met simultaneously with the major street warrant 11 hours out of
the 12 total hours that were counted. Table 1 shows eight hours with the highest traffic volume of
the 12 that were counted. Therefore, Condition A was met for this warrant.

The Four-Hour Vehicular Volume signal warrant conditions are intended to be applied where the
volume of intersecting traffic is the principal reason to consider installing a traffic control signal.
The need for a traffic control signal shall be considered if an engineering study finds that, for
each of any 4 hours of an average day, the plotted points representing the vehicles per hour on the
major street (total of both approaches) and the corresponding vehicles per hour on the higher-
volume minor-street approach (one direction only) all fall above the applicable curve in Figure
4C-1 for the existing combination of approach lanes. On the minor street, the higher volume shall
not be required to be on the same approach during each of these 4 hours.
